<section class="main-content">
<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<hr />
<p>In 2017, Instacart provided anonymized data on Kaggle describing customers’ orders over time.</p>
<p>The dataset contains a sample of over 3 million grocery orders from more than 200,000 Instacart users. For each user, Instacart provided between 4 and 100 of their orders, with the sequence of products purchased in each order. It also provided the week and hour of day the order was placed, and a relative measure of time between orders.</p>
<p><strong>Our objective is to predict which products will be in a user’s next order.</strong></p>
</div>

<div id="understanding-the-data" class="section level1">
<h1>Understanding the data</h1>
<hr />
<p>The dataset consists of information about 3.4 million grocery orders, distributed across 6 csv files. In this section, we focus on getting a good preliminary understanding of our data before going into deeper analysis.</p>
<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">data_list &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">list</span>(products, aisles, departments, order_products_prior, order_products_train, orders)
<span class="kw">plot_str</span>(data_list)</code></pre></div>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p><strong>Products</strong>: Contains the names of the products with their corresponding product_id. Aisle and department IDs are also included.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Aisles</strong>: Contains the id and the names of the different aisles</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Departments</strong>: Contains the id and the names of the different departments.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Order_products_prior</strong>: Contains product information (product_id) and user order information such as add to cart order, and whether the product was reordered.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Order_products_train</strong>: Structure is similar to <strong>Order_products_prior</strong>, but information only about each order that is used for training.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Orders</strong>: List of all orders in the dataset, with 1 row per order. Each order is classified as prior, train, test. For example, user 1 has 11 orders - 10 classified as prior, and the last 1 as train. No product information is included.</p></li>
</ol>
<div id="understanding-orders-table" class="section level2">

<div class="sourceCode"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r">Mode &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="cf">function</span>(x) {
  ux &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">unique</span>(x)
  ux[<span class="kw">which.max</span>(<span class="kw">tabulate</span>(<span class="kw">match</span>(x, ux)))]
}

<span class="co">#number of orders by products  </span>
